Thanks to all students who responded!  We had so many great catchy headlines that capture the main ideas of the map:  “Swing to the Left, Swing to the Right” by Yomi in Minnesota; “Party Power Shift” by Mo of Indiana; "US Elections: To Be More Red or To Be More Blue?" by Joseph of Boston; “Shifting and Flipping of Votes in the US” by Jesus of Illinois; “Making Waves: States Flip Sides” by Kelsee of Salt Lake Center for Science Education; and “Are You Indecisive? Maybe Your State Is, Too!: Party Shifting in US States Since 2004” by Lauren of Academy of Saint Elizabeth in Morristown, New Jersey;

You can continue to post responses.  Please check back by Friday, Jan. 15 to see the Reveal with some questions about the graph and a few Stat Nuggets.  (There is no link to the original New York Times article since this graph only appeared in the print version.

Signing off – Sharon Hessney of Boston, who lives in state which has always voted Democratic for president but usually has a Republican governor, and George Carr,  mathematics teacher at St. Joseph’s High School and Clemson University in Greenville, South Carolina, who worked at the polls this past November for the first time ever and found it to be an absolutely fascinating, as well as rewarding, experience.

